{META_DATA}: AMERICAN GANGSTER
{META_DATA}: Written by
{META_DATA}: Steven Zaillian
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FINAL SHOOTING SCRIPT
{DIALOGUE}: July 27, 2006
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 1 EXT. JAZZ CLUB - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tall, handsome man in a dark suit emerges from a Lincoln Towncar and enters a small, basement R&B/Jazz club.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 2 INT. JAZZ CLUB - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He approaches a booth, says something in the din to the men there, then calmly shoots them and exits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: AMERICAN GANGSTER
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 3 EXT. HARLEM STREET - DAY (NOVEMBER)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy Johnson, an elderly but still sturdy black man, elegantly dressed - cashmere overcoat, gloves, Homburg - stands in falling snow atop a flatbed truck - as he does every Thanksgiving - tossing down turkeys to the poor - like a benign king.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: Harlem
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A younger man, the gunman from the club - Frank Lucas - Bumpy's driver/bodyguard/collector/protege - watches from below.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 4 INT/EXT. STREET / DISCOUNT EMPORIUM - DAY (NOVEMBER)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whispering gunfire from a television set veiled by foreground snow: Soldiers in the jungles of Vietnam in 1970.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A rich, cultured, authoritative voice offers:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY O/S
{DIALOGUE}: This is the problem.
{DIALOGUE}: This is what's wrong with America.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The war footage multiplies by twenty: a stack of TVs with price tags dangling from the knobs behind a display window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY O/S
{DIALOGUE}: It's gotten so big you can't find your way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: People on the sidewalk, out of respect or fear, part to let Frank and Bumpy and Bumpy's German shepherd pass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: The corner grocery's a supermarket.
{DIALOGUE}: Candy store's a MacDonald's.
{DIALOGUE}: And this place.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{META_DATA}: 4 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Where's the pride of ownership here?
{DIALOGUE}: Where's the personal service?
{DIALOGUE}: Does anybody work here?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside, the emporium is vast, with aisles that seem to stretch off into infinity.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The TVs give way to a display window full of Japanese stereo componentry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: What right do they have cutting out the suppliers, pushing all the middlemen out, buying direct from the manufacturer - Sony this, Toshiba that, all them Chinks - putting Americans out of work?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's not really asking Frank, so Frank doesn't answer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: What am I supposed to do with a place like this, Frank?
{DIALOGUE}: Who am I supposed to ask for, the assistant manager?
{META_DATA}: (pause)
{DIALOGUE}: This is the problem.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the way it is now: You can't find the heart of anything to stick the knife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy stops before a display of cameras and stares in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're all pointed at him as a pain grips his chest and he sinks to his knees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank kneels down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy seems unable to speak, looks to Frank confused.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Somebody call an ambulance!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the store suddenly seems empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank yells into the emporium but can't be heard above the Muzak and the cash registers ringing up sales Bumpy will never see a piece of.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking up at Frank, Bumpy manages weakly -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: Forget it, Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: No one's in charge.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 5 EXT. BUMPY'S APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Limousines from the funeral disgorge mourners: family, friends, celebrities, politicians.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cops on horseback move through the enormous crowd that has gathered to watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FBI agents in cars snap pictures with long lenses of Italian mobsters like Albert Tosca.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3.
{META_DATA}: 5 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: - whose passing has brought together a who's who of mourners on this chilly afternoon.
{DIALOGUE}: The Governor has come down.
{DIALOGUE}: The mayor of New York - its Chief of Police and Commissioner - sports and entertainment luminaries -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A white Bentley pulls up, disgorging Jackie Fox - the original Superfly - and his entourage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With his trademark tinted Gucci glasses on, he happily poses for anyone with a camera - including the Feds - before going inside.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 6 INT. BUMPY'S APARTMENT - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The report continues on a TV no one's really watching here: a March of Time-like history of Bumpy Johnson, famed Harlem gangster, Robin Hood and killer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER ON TV
{DIALOGUE}: He was a Great Man, according to the eulogies.
{DIALOGUE}: A giving man.
{DIALOGUE}: A man of the people.
{DIALOGUE}: No one chose to include in their remembrances the word most often associated with Ellsworth Bumpy Johnson: Gangster.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting off by himself in Bumpy's elegant garden apartment, heretofore his private sanctuary, Frank surveys the mourners circling the place like vultures:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tango Black, a huge brute, scavenging the catered food and tended bar ... Jackie Fox, surrounded by his ever-present coterie of sycophants ... Albert Tosca, an elegant Italian capo, and an underling, Rossi, at the bar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: White wine, please.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A white man who looks like a banker - and is - sits down next to Frank.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANKER
{DIALOGUE}: How you doing, Frank?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANKER
{DIALOGUE}: What a loss.
{META_DATA}: (Frank nods)
{DIALOGUE}: How are you otherwise?
{DIALOGUE}: Things okay financially?
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 4.
{META_DATA}: 6 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank doesn't say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It feels unseemly to him to be talking about money here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He watches Tango carelessly set a watery glass of ice on an antique inlaid chess table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANKER
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy set something up for you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank excuses himself without an answer, crosses to where Tango left the glass, and sets it on a coaster.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Frank, get me an ashtray while you're at it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy's German shepherd watches as Frank reaches into his jacket, revealing a gun nestled in its shoulder holster.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes out a handkerchief, wipes the condensation dry, opens a drawer and removes an ashtray.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He holds it out to Tango - who isn't sure it's not a dare and decides to wander off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: I know you're hurting, Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: So am I.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank sits back down with Charlie Williams, an older dope man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: You going to be all right?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sure Bumpy never told you, but he made me promise, anything ever happened to him, I'd make sure you didn't go without.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be fine, Charlie.
{DIALOGUE}: Half the people here owed Bumpy money when he died.
{DIALOGUE}: A lot of money.
{DIALOGUE}: If they think I'm going to forget to collect, they're wrong.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: That's the spirit.
{DIALOGUE}: Go get them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the TV, over archive film and photographs of crime figures from the 1940's and `50's, the opinion is offered that Bumpy's death "marks the end of an era ..."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 5.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A7 INT. CLASSROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A figure, his back to us, walks slowly toward a blackboard like a man to the gallows.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE V.O.
{DIALOGUE}: I live in fear of hearing my name called.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROFESSOR
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Roberts, Give us U.S. vs. Meade -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE V.O.
{DIALOGUE}: Of walking up there, turning around, knowing every one of them knows more than I do -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROFESSOR
{DIALOGUE}: Subject, issues, what the determination was and what it means to us today.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie Roberts turns and faces his classmates, all of them a decade or more younger than him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 7 EXT. MOTEL - NEW JERSEY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harlem's jagged teeth skyline juts across the river at the other end of the George Washington Bridge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On this side - a sledgehammer gripped in Richie's fist, on the move, suddenly fills the frame.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You know the Number 1 fear of most people isn't dying; it's public speaking.
{DIALOGUE}: They get physically ill.
{DIALOGUE}: They throw up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: And that's what you want to do for a living.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't like being like that.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to beat it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Armed with the sledgehammer, Richie and his partner - Javy Rivera - come past a seedy motel office where a TV shows another report about Bumpy Johnson.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: New Jersey
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A motel clerk looks up, glimpses the sledgehammer -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 6.
{META_DATA}: 7 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLERK
{DIALOGUE}: Hey -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera flashes a New Jersey detective's shield without breaking stride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Takes a subpoena out of another pocket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Who's going to do this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: He knows me, he'll take it from me.
{DIALOGUE}: I've known him since high school.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Just throw it in, he doesn't take it.
{DIALOGUE}: That's good service.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They reach a particular motel room door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera knocks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens the length of a chain, revealing a wise guy in an undershirt, who, when he sees the subpoena, start to close the door -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Throw it -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Richie flings the subpoena in, the door slams on his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wails in agony, tries to shoulder it open, hears the dead bolt lock on the other side, feels Campizi's teeth bite into his fingers, watches his blood run down the frame.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Down -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie hangs down from his hand as the sledgehammer swings past his head shattering the door -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 8 INT/EXT. MOTEL ROOM - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door rips from its hinges and the detectives crash in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The wise guy - Campizi - hurries for the bathroom, slams the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This one's hollow and the detectives more easily break through it -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Campizi tries to climb out the bathroom window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie grabs him, throws him into the shower stall, taking the plastic curtain down with them, smearing it with blood as Richie beats at him before Rivera can pull him off.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 9 INT. AMBULANCE - MOVING - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A male paramedic attends to Campizi's bloodied face while a female paramedic cleans Richie's bloodied hand.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 7.
{META_DATA}: 9 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAMPIZI
{DIALOGUE}: I swear to God, Richie, I didn't know it was you.
{DIALOGUE}: I would never slam a door on your hand.
{DIALOGUE}: Knowingly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You bit my fuckin hand -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie lunges at him, hits him again with his injured hand - which hurts Richie more than it does Campizi.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The paramedics manage to pull him away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAMPIZI
{DIALOGUE}: What can we do, Richie?
{DIALOGUE}: You don't want to do this.
{DIALOGUE}: For old times sake, what can we do?
{DIALOGUE}: Who do you want?
{DIALOGUE}: Who can I give you?
{DIALOGUE}: You want Big Sal's bookie?
{DIALOGUE}: You want his accountant?
{DIALOGUE}: I'll give him to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie regards him a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A policy ring's accountant wouldn't be bad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He glances back to his paramedic dabbing at his bloody hand, and notices she's not bad-looking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smiles back.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 10 INT. NY POLICE HQ - ENTRANCE/STAIRS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Four men in long black leather coats stride toward like they own the city.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's impossible to tell if they're cops or gangsters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: New York City
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 11 INT. NEW YORK POLICE ANNEX - PROPERTY ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of the same undercover cops - Detective Trupo - scribbles a signature and badge number different from the one on his gold shield lying next to the voucher requesting evidence needed in court.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pushes the voucher under a sign - "All Handguns and Narcotics Before 10am Next Window" - to a clerk who takes it past floor-to-ceiling shelves covered with files, plastic bags bulging with handguns, knives and gambling receipts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bulkier items - like shotguns and baseball bats - lie unwrapped with dangling tags.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The clerk reaches a chain-link cage where the most valuable items are locked up - narcotics, pornography, cash - checks the voucher against tags, takes down an old green suitcase.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 8.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 12 EXT. WAREHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo's car - a Shelby Mustang - roars up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs out, crosses to a warehouse with the suitcase as the other three SIU Princes of the City follow from another car, cradling grocery bags.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 13 INT. WAREHOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo snaps the suitcase open revealing five half-kilo bags of uncut heroin in clear plastic bags.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other cops pull from the grocery bags: a Pyrex mixing bowl, flour sifter, boxes of milk-sugar, latex kitchen gloves, a medical scale, and yellow baggies.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hands peel back the distinctive black and green "evidence" tape on the clear plastic bags.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dump the heroin into twenty yellow baggies.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A half-kilo of lactose is poured into each of the now-empty property room bags.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TRUPO
{DIALOGUE}: Now just enough for the reagent test.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He removes one tablespoon of heroin from each of the baggies, and the now-almost-heroin-free powder is mixed through the flour sifter, poured back into the clear bags, the tape resealed, the bags returned to the suitcase.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 14 INT. NY COURTROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The suitcase and "heroin," and some weapons and money, have been arranged on an evidence table with the care of a Macy's display window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo - the officer in charge of the case - watches the jury files in -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 15 EXT. UNDER EXPRESSWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Lincoln Continental pulls up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo climbs out of his Shelby with a sports bag, crosses to the Lincoln, climbs in back where an Italian wise guy - Rossi - sits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo unzips the bag revealing the recut heroin - in the yellow plastic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI V/O
{DIALOGUE}: This is the French Connection dope.
{DIALOGUE}: The same dope Popeye Doyle and Sonny Grasso took from us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 16 OMIT 16 OMIT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 9.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 17 INT. ITALIAN BAR - NY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank comes into an empty bar, chairs up on tables.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A middle-aged man mopping up glances up at him as he crosses to a back room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI V/O
{DIALOGUE}: They seize it, arrest everybody, whack it up and sell it back to us.
{DIALOGUE}: Our dope.
{DIALOGUE}: They been living off it for years, these New York cops.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 18 INT. ITALIAN BAR - BACK ROOM - NY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several ounces of the dope sits in foreground on a table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI
{DIALOGUE}: They basically control the market with it.
{DIALOGUE}: What the fuck has happened to the world, Frank?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Fuckin crooks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rossi, who looks more like a middle-aged accountant than the Italian dope supplier he is, makes two espressos.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI
{DIALOGUE}: Sad about Bumpy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind Frank, a TV airs a report by Walter Cronkite on the heroin problem among GIs in Vietnam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI
{DIALOGUE}: Things are never going to be the same in Harlem.
{DIALOGUE}: The girls, the clubs, the music - walk down the street, nobody bothers you because Bumpy's making sure of it.
{META_DATA}: (hands Frank one of the espressos)
{DIALOGUE}: How bad is it there now?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18pt FLASHCUTS TO HARLEM 18pt
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Guys barge into a room, steal money from a crap game at gunpoint - Cops push guys against a bar, empty their pockets - A dealer shoots another dealer in an alley -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18pt BACK TO THE HOTEL ROOM 18pt
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: It's chaos.
{DIALOGUE}: Every gorilla for himself.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 10.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18pt CONTINUED: 18pt
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROSSI
{DIALOGUE}: Who can live like that?
{DIALOGUE}: There has to be order.
{DIALOGUE}: That would never happen with Italians.
{DIALOGUE}: More important than any one man's life - is order.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 19 EXT. HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A street sign on a corner: 116th and 8th Avenue.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 20 INT. DINER - HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As is his custom, Frank eats breakfast alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A middle- aged waitress appears when he's done, picks up his plate and refills his coffee.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, Charlene.
{DIALOGUE}: Last one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLENE
{DIALOGUE}: It's all right with me, Frank, you can stay all day if you want, but I wouldn't.
{DIALOGUE}: It's nice outside.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Then maybe I'll have to go for a walk.
{DIALOGUE}: Just cause you said so.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smiles and leaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank pours some sugar in his coffee.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Someone taps on the window and he looks up, sees two servicemen - one in uniform - one he recognizes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 21 INT. REDTOP'S APARTMENT BUILDING - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank leads the servicemen up the stairs of a building.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 22 INT. REDTOP'S APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Corner apartment above the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A girl sits smoking at a work table covered with drug-cutting apparatus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another - Frank's cutter and sometimes-girlfriend, Red Top - sets a couple of packets of heroin in front of the servicemen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RED TOP
{DIALOGUE}: On the house for our men in uniform.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SERVICEMAN 1
{DIALOGUE}: Why, thank you, sugar, that's very kind.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RED TOP
{DIALOGUE}: Thank Frank.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 11.
{META_DATA}: 22 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank nods, you're welcome before the man can thank him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The servicemen start cooking up the dope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: How's Nate?
{DIALOGUE}: You seen him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SERVICEMAN 1
{DIALOGUE}: All the time.
{DIALOGUE}: Nate is everywhere.
{DIALOGUE}: He's good.
{DIALOGUE}: Got himself a club now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Where, Saigon?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SERVICEMAN 1
{DIALOGUE}: Bangkok.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SERVICEMAN 2
{DIALOGUE}: I don't think he's ever coming home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Regarding the dope as the servicemen shoot it up -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You're gonna have to boot it a couple times.
{DIALOGUE}: Cops keep cutting it, selling it, cutting it -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SERVICEMAN 1
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to say anything cause the price is right - but the shit in Nam is way, way, way, way, way -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins to nod out before he can finish the sentence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 23 OMIT 23 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 24 EXT. SOCIAL CLUB - NEWARK - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Across the river, Richie, Rivera and Campizi sit in the car parked across from a closed social club.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A man carrying a grocery bag comes out and Campizi ducks lower in the seat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAMPIZI
{DIALOGUE}: That's him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Newsboy Moriarty's mob accountant puts the grocery bag in the trunk of a car, climbs in behind the wheel.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 25 EXT. NEWARK - SCRAP METAL YARD - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From the parked car they observe the accountant putting another bag in his trunk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 12.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 26 EXT. STREET - NEWARK - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes out of another place with another bag.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To Campizi -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: Get lost.
{DIALOGUE}: Get out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Campizi slinks out of the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie and Rivera follow after Newsboy Moriarty's accountant's car.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 27 EXT. PARKING LOT - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They tail the car into a lot, park and watch the accountant leave his car and get into another car that's parked there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: We gonna stay with him or the car?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever they do, they'll have to decide quick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Let's see who comes for the car.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 28 EXT. PARKING LOT - NEWARK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All the other cars are gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera climbs into Richie's with coffee and a Coke in a bag, hands him the can.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Think he made us?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie doesn't know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Glances at his watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cranes in his seat to look behind them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You called for the warrant?
{DIALOGUE}: Where are they?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: I just called.
{DIALOGUE}: I called and walked back here and ten seconds has gone by.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie watches an attendant lock up, listens to the street lamps buzz, grows impatient.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Indicating the other car:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: We saw him with the slips, Javy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: You saw policy slips?
{DIALOGUE}: You saw grocery bags.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't know what's in them.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 13.
{META_DATA}: 28 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, I do, and so do you, don't give me that bullshit -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: What's the rush?
{DIALOGUE}: Half an hour the warrant'll be here -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I got night school.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Guess you're going to miss it.
{META_DATA}: (Rivera sips at his coffee; then:)
{DIALOGUE}: You know, what you were saying before - about throwing up in front of people - money will take that feeling away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Not when it's less.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Less than what.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Than what I make now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: No lawyer on earth makes less than a cop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: They do in the Prosecutor's Office.
{DIALOGUE}: Three thousand less.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: You're fuckin kidding me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie isn't kidding.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera stares at him like he's crazy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie checks his watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's waited long enough.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck this -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Richie -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie gets out, opens the trunk, grabs a Slimjim and bolt cutters, cuts through a gate chain and strides to the accountant's car, Rivera following.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie trips the passenger door lock and pulls at the trunk release, and, as he comes around back to search it -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 14.
{META_DATA}: 28 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Check inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera may as well; the damage to the case, if there is one anymore, is done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He crawls inside the car to look under the seats and in the glove compartment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gravely -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Javy ...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie's staring into the trunk like there's a body inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rivera comes over, takes a look, sees it's money: stacks of it rubber-banded together, spilling from grocery bags - more than either of them has ever seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the trunk closes -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 29 EXT. PARKING LOT / RICHIE'S CAR - LATER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie and Rivera sit in their car in silence, staring out at the car with the money in it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't a couple of bucks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: It's the same thing.
{DIALOGUE}: In principle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: We're talking about principle?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Richie, a cop who turns in this kind of money says one thing: He'll turn in cops who take money.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll be pariahs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: We're fucked either way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Not if we keep it.
{DIALOGUE}: Only if we don't.
{DIALOGUE}: Then we're fucked, you're right.
{DIALOGUE}: But not if we keep it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{META_DATA}: (more to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, we are.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RIVERA
{DIALOGUE}: Goddamn it, did we ask for this?
{DIALOGUE}: Did we put a gun to someone's head and say, Give us your money?
{DIALOGUE}: Cops kill cops they can't trust.
{DIALOGUE}: We can't turn it in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They regard each other again in silence ...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 15.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 30 INT. NEWARK POLICE STATION - LATER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As a police captain counts the stacks of money, Lou Toback, Richie's superior from the prosecutors office, walks in, his night out interrupted by this emergency.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He crossed to where Richie and Rivera sit alone in a corner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Quietly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: How much.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Nine hundred and eighty thousand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: What happened to the rest?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a joke but isn't funny, not even to Toback.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He regards his men who turned it in, then the other cops in the place - who are watching them and the money being counted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback walks over to the captain, and, quietly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: What're you doing counting this in front of everybody?
{DIALOGUE}: Are you out of your fuckin mind?
{DIALOGUE}: Take it into a room.
{DIALOGUE}: Now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie's glance to Rivera says, You're right, we're fucked.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 31 INT/EXT. NEWARK POLICE STATION - PRE-DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Richie leaves alone, he's aware of all the eyes on him - knowing the other cops' looks don't signify awe or respect, but contempt and fear, like Rivera predicted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Neither will ever be trusted again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs into his car, drives off.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 32 INT. DINER - HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tango and his bodyguard come in and approach Frank's table where he reads the morning paper as he eats breakfast.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Didn't you see the jar, Frank?
{DIALOGUE}: I think you walked right past it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank ignores him, forks at his eggs, eats.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tango sits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: The money jar.
{DIALOGUE}: On the corner.
{DIALOGUE}: What I got to do, put a sign on it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank indicates that he would answer if his mouth wasn't full.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swallows finally, but then only reaches for his coffee cup to take a sip, further irritating Tango.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 16.
{META_DATA}: 32 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy don't own 116th Street no more, Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy don't own no real estate in Harlem no more.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm the landlord now and the lease is twenty-percent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank dabs at his mouth with a napkin and gives Tango a look that says that won't be happening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Then don't sell dope, Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: Get a fuckin job.
{DIALOGUE}: You need a job?
{DIALOGUE}: You can be my driver, drive me around, open my door, yes, sir, no sir, where to, sir, right away, Massa Johnson, sir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Right now Tango is dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No doubt about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the surface, though, Frank remains cool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty percent?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Of every dollar.
{DIALOGUE}: Every VIG, every truckload, every girl, every ounce.
{DIALOGUE}: In the jar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty percent's my profit.
{DIALOGUE}: If I'm giving it to you then what am I doing?
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty percent puts me, and everyone you know, out of business, which puts you out of business.
{META_DATA}: (reaches for his breakfast check)
{DIALOGUE}: There are ways to make money legitimately, and then there's this way.
{DIALOGUE}: Not even Bumpy took twenty percent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy's fuckin dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank regards Tango a moment, gets up, takes out his money clip, covers the check on the table with a five, peels off a $1 bill from the clip, tosses it down in front of Tango.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: There.
{DIALOGUE}: That's twenty-percent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he turns and leaves, Tango watches after him ...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 17.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 33 INT. RICHIE'S APARTMENT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stitched-up, black and blue hands dump a can of soup in a pot, put it on the stove.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 34 INT. FRANK'S APARTMENT - NIGHT - INTERCUT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A pencil clutched by long fingers scribbles figures.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But no matter how many times Frank does the arithmetic, there's not much left, he calculates, after he pays the Italian suppliers and, if he were to, Tango.
{META_DATA}: 35 INT. RICHIE'S APARTMENT - NIGHT - CONTINUED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie has moved to a small desk cluttered with law textbooks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He cracks one open to study for the New Jersey Bar exam as he eats the soup out of the pot he heated it in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Above him on the wall is a framed photograph of Joe Louis standing over a sprawled-on-the-mat Billy Conn.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 36 EXT. CONEY ISLAND - BEACH - DAY - INTERCUT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bleak day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seagulls fighting over scraps on the sand as others hover overhead, flapping and cawing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Alone near the water, Frank tosses a stick for the German shepherd he inherited.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 37 INT. RICHIE'S APARTMENT - NIGHT - INTERCUT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie opens a small wooden box in his bleak apartment, revealing an ounce of marijuana, rolling papers and clips.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he rolls a joint -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY V/O
{DIALOGUE}: A leader is like a shepherd -
{META_DATA}: 38 EXT. CONEY ISLAND - BEACH - DAY - CONTINUED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sounds of the gulls and surf and roller coaster begin to fade as Frank throws the stick again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY V/O
{DIALOGUE}: Sends the fast nimble sheep out front, and the others follow as the shepherd walks quietly behind -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The dog retrieves the stick, but this time - somehow - it's to Bumpy's hand he returns it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank listens attentively.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: He's got the stick - the cane - and he'll use if he has to.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18.
{META_DATA}: 38 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But most of the time he doesn't have to.
{DIALOGUE}: He moves the whole herd - quietly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy smiles and tosses the stick.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 39 INT. RICHIE'S APARTMENT - NIGHT - INTERCUT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The smoke from the joint rises to the ceiling as Richie studies.
{META_DATA}: 40 EXT. CONEY ISLAND - BEACH - DAY - CONTINUED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The dog trots back to Bumpy and Frank with the stick.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 41 EXT. BOARDWALK - CONEY ISLAND - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hot dog stand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bumpy hands a hot dog to Frank, holds out another to the shepherd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To camera:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUMPY
{DIALOGUE}: What right do they have cutting out the suppliers, the middlemen, buying direct, putting Americans out of work ... This is the way it is now, Frank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The vender hands him a napkin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The shepherd is still with him, but Bumpy is gone, and the gulls and the people on the roller coaster squeal as Frank comes out of his meditative trance with an idea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 42 CLOSE-UP: (DOCTOR'S OFFICE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A needle pierces the crook of Frank's arm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slight grimace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cotton ball is pushed onto the puncture.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Malaria shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 43 CLOSE-UP: (PHOTOGRAPHY SHOP)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A strobe lights up Frank's face: a passport photo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 44 CLOSE-UP: (POST OFFICE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The photo and a duplicate are stapled to a passport application.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 45 INT. CHEMICAL BANK - SAFETY-DEPOSIT ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Keys turn the locks of a safety-deposit box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lid lifts revealing decks of cash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank takes it all out, slips one slender packet into Bumpy's banker's jacket pocket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Get yourself a new suit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 19.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 46 INT. CHEMICAL BANK - VICE PRESIDENT'S OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under portraits of bank Vice Presidents before him, the man types out a Chemical Bank check for Frank for $400,000.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 47 - 48 OMIT 47 - 48 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 49 EXT. PARK - NEWARK - DAY - SAME TIME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sound of the plane growls and fades overhead as Richie's ex-wife keeps an eye on their son playing on a grassy area.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LAURIE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know, Richie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: It couldn't be avoided.
{DIALOGUE}: Next weekend I'll be able to take him.
