{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 78 EXT. HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Frank leads his brothers down the sidewalk, the Towncar that was parked at the Teaneck house, driven by Frank's body- guard, Doc, follows alongside at the same pace they walk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I was with him every day for fifteen of them, looking after him, taking care of things, protecting him, learning from him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The brothers can't help but notice the storekeepers who wave to Frank, the women who smile, the men who step out of his path like there's a red carpet under his polished shoes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy was rich, but never white man rich.
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{DIALOGUE}: Because he didn't own the company.
{DIALOGUE}: He thought he did.
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't.
{DIALOGUE}: He only managed it.
