{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank pushes the door open, revealing -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 80 INT. REDTOP'S APARTMENT - CONTINUOUS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Five naked women at work tables, their faces veiled by surgical masks, cutting heroin with lactose and quinine in a precise mixture of controlled purity.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Lucas brothers stare as the supervisor of the activity - clothed, with red hair - comes over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REDTOP
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, Frank.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, these are my brothers.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 81 EXT. HARLEM - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tango strolls down the street like he's the Godfather of Harlem, girl on his arm, bodyguard at his side.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 82 INT. DINER - SAME TIME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As his brothers eat lunch, Frank - who can see Tango outside - uncaps a glass sugar container.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: What matters in business is honesty, integrity, hard work, loyalty, and never forgetting where you came from.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For reasons his brothers can't imagine, Frank empties all sugar from the container onto his plate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You are what you are and that's one of two things.
{DIALOGUE}: You're nothing ... or you're something.
{DIALOGUE}: Understand what I'm saying?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The brothers nod tentatively, stare at the now-empty glass container.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank wipes his mouth with a napkin, gets up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be right back.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 83 EXT/INT. DINER - MOMENTS LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes out of the diner, crosses the street toward Tango, who's buying fruit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Greets him cheerfully -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Tango, what's up.
{DIALOGUE}: I was just thinking about you.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 38.
{META_DATA}: 83 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I was looking at the jar and you know what?
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't see nothing in it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: The fuck you want, Frank -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before the last word is out of Tango's mouth, Frank's got a gun pressed against his forehead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone backs away - the bodyguard, too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tango's girl pulls her arm from his and takes off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TANGO
{DIALOGUE}: What're you going to do, boy?
{DIALOGUE}: Shoot me in broad daylight?
{DIALOGUE}: In front of everyone?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's as if life on the street has stopped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one moves; everyone is looking at Frank; maybe that's what he wants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Tango laughs at the thought -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that's right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank pulls the trigger and the big man falls back like someone hit with a board.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank stands over him and empties the gun in his chest, the shots echoing down the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then it's quiet again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone's still looking him, but Frank doesn't run.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Instead, he calmly reaches into Tango's suit pocket, takes out a money clip thick with cash, drops it in the "jar" and sets it next to the body.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: For the cops.
{DIALOGUE}: Should be enough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank returns to the diner and sits back down, ignoring the astonished stares from his brothers and everyone else in the place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tries to remember where he was in his lecture as he tucks the napkin back in his shirt collar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: That basically's the whole picture right there.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 84 INT. MORGUE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cadaver drawer slides open revealing - not Tango - but Rivera, staring up lifeless, his arms, stomach, legs and toes dotted with the scabs of a longtime addict.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: Did you know his girlfriend?
{DIALOGUE}: Good- looking girl.
{DIALOGUE}: One of his informants.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 39.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Beth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The medical examiner slides open another cadaver drawer containing her body.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie stares at it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: Should've seen their place.
{DIALOGUE}: Like animals lived there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I have seen it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{META_DATA}: (to the examiner)
{DIALOGUE}: Chose a good night, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Grand Central Station in here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MEDICAL EXAMINER
{DIALOGUE}: It's been like this.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm lucky I get home before midnight; lots of careless- ness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie regards Rivera's personal effects resting on his chest in a plastic bag: few bucks, the Corvette key, a half- empty packet of heroin in blue cellophane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie takes the blue cellophane from the bag and, as the drawer closes entombing Sanders, holds it in his hand ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER V/O
{DIALOGUE}: Heroin addiction is no longer exclusive to big city neighborhoods; it's epidemic -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 85 TIME CUT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A TELEVISION: The reports shows lawmakers on Capitol Hill juxtaposed against images of inner-cities, junkies, homicide victims and, perhaps most telling, white suburbia.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER ON TV
{DIALOGUE}: Since 1965, law enforcement has watched its steady increase and with it a rise in violent crime.
{DIALOGUE}: Now unaccountably, it has exploded, reaching into cities as a whole - our suburbs and towns - our schools.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. POLICE GYM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The TV is in a small police gym where Richie lifts weights, very much aware of his pariah status as out-of-shape cops come in, only to leave again when they see him.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 40.
{META_DATA}: CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER ON TV
{DIALOGUE}: Someone is finally saying: enough.
{DIALOGUE}: Federal authorities have announced their intention to establish special narcotics bureaus in Washington, New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Boston, Newark and other major cities -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback comes in, watches Richie, alone, working out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE V/O
{DIALOGUE}: It's a dog and pony show.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK V/O
{DIALOGUE}: It's not being advertised as one.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 86 INT. POLICE GYM - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie's changing into his street clothes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: But it's federal.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd have to answer to who?
{DIALOGUE}: FBI?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: Me and the U.S. Attorney.
{DIALOGUE}: No one else.
{DIALOGUE}: No FBI.
{DIALOGUE}: Hoover knows better than to mix his men with dope.
{DIALOGUE}: Too much temptation for the feeble-minded.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though he's not in much of a position to refuse the assignment, Richie still isn't convinced it's a good idea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback levels with him -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: Richie, a detective who doesn't have the cooperation of his fellow detectives can't be effective.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You know why I don't have it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: Doesn't matter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: No, they're all on the take and I'm not and it doesn't matter to anyone.
{DIALOGUE}: Instead of giving you a medal for turning in money, they bury you.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 41.
{META_DATA}: 86 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: It's fucked up.
{DIALOGUE}: You're right.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe this's an opportunity away from all that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They regard each other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'll do it, but only like this: I don't set foot in a police station again.
{DIALOGUE}: I work out of a place of my own.
{DIALOGUE}: And I pick my own guys.
{DIALOGUE}: Guys I know wouldn't take a nickel off the sidewalk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: Done.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 87 EXT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old building that was once an Episcopal church.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 88 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
