{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 107 INT/EXT. CAR / STREET - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Abruzzo, looking like a junkie, dirty jeans, wool cap, approaches a dealer on the corner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The perspective shifts to Richie, Spearman and Jones in a car, watching as Abruzzo chats briefly with the dealer before the exchange takes place: $10 for a blue-cellophane packet.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 108 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie and the others watch Jones tests the heroin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: Stuff's ten percent pure.
{DIALOGUE}: Strong enough to smoke for all those suburban white kids afraid of needles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other detectives are exchange a glance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: None has ever heard of anything on the street that pure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You paid ten bucks for it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: And it's all that's out there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Now, how is that possible?
{DIALOGUE}: Who can afford to sell shit twice as good for half as much?
{DIALOGUE}: Richie glances to a Table of Organization: Surveillance photos haphazardly thumb-tacked to a bulletin board - known dope men in the hierarchies of their individual crime families - almost all of them Italian.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WOMB TO TOMB SEQUENCE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An R & B song begins and continues over -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 109 CLOSE-UPS:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A poppy bulb being pierced, the white liquid oozing, changing into filthy liquids in wooden bowls, and finally a gray paste ...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 110 INT. BANK VICE PRESIDENT'S OFFICE - CHEMICAL BANK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank sits with the bank Vice President who wires a transfer to:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 50.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 111 INT. BANGKOK BANK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Where Nate sits with the same Thai bank president as before who converts the transfer to cash.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 112 INT. SOUL BROTHERS BAR - BANGKOK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nate slides cash across a table to a couple of Chinese gangsters.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 113 EXT. JUNGLE ARMY BASE - VIETNAM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tent: Nate hands more cash - the military brass's cut - to the 2-star general from before.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An airstrip: Slicing propellers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wounded soldiers on stretchers, helped onto a transport plane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, four large crates - Japanese TVs - under cargo netting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The pilot stuffs more cash in a pouch and salutes Nate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 114 TV IMAGE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: General Westmoreland returns a salute (archive).
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 115 EXT. ARMY BASE - NORTH CAROLINA - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same plane on the tarmac here, taxiing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A pile of discarded TV boxes outside a supply warehouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the perimeter of the base, black servicemen transfer heavy taped-up duffel bags from an Army Jeep to a station wagon, hoisting those that won't fit inside onto a roof rack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two Lucas brothers tie them down with twine.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 116 INT/EXT. CAR / HIGHWAY - NEAR WASHINGTON DC - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The station wagon heading north on a rain-slicked highway, the canvas tarpaulin on top flapping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, the spire of the Washington monument glows.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 117 EXT. DISCOUNT DRUGSTORE - HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A black woman pushes a shopping cart containing a baby, Pampers, and cases of milk sugar across a parking lot.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 118 INT. RED TOP'S APARTMENT - HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Empty milk sugar boxes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Redtop and her five table workers - clothed now, the surgical masks dangling from their necks - wiping down table surfaces, scales and apparatus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tens of thousands of blue-cellophane packets of heroin neatly cover two of the folding tables.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 51.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 119 EXT. HARLEM STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: August.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Kids wrench open a fire hydrant and with an empty soda can direct the water into a fountain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The water sprays down onto the windshield of a beat-up Chevy coming slowly through, revealing when it clears, Frank behind the wheel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He parks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Glances at his watch.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 120 INT. NYPD 23RD PRECINCT - LOCKER ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clock on the wall of a locker area: 3:58.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shift change.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cops in t-shirts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fans blowing the humid air around.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 121 INT/EXT. NYPD 23RD PRECINCT GARAGE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Blue and whites arriving and leaving, shirts coming off as the cops alight.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 122 INT. BUS - MOVING ON 116TH STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The driver checks his watch: 3:59.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Turns his almost-empty bus up 8th Avenue.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 123 INT/EXT. FRANK'S PARKED CHEVY - HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Air conditioner full blast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radio announcing the time: 4 o'clock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank glances out the wet windshield of the Chevy and watches 116th Street transform:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's as if an outdoor market has just opened its stalls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Junkies and dealers emerging from the alleys, storefronts, tenements and side streets - from the street itself it seems - snarling the cars and delivery trucks caught unaware.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Small blue cellophane packets - and only blue - are pulled from pockets and change hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In alleyways it's cooked up and sucked into syringes, and in dank, grim, indescribably filthy rooms, plunged into veins -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 124 AND THE REVERSE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 10 and 20 dollar bills changing hands - decks of cash rubber-banded together - put into envelopes and delivered to the Lucas brothers, to:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 125 LESTER at his metal door shop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 126 EUGENE at his dry cleaners.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 127 TURNER at his tire service shop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 128 EARL at his electrical shop.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 52.
{META_DATA}: 123 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 129 TEDDY at his body shop.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 130 INT. REDTOP'S APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Piles of cash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The brothers try counting it all, but it's just too much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's actually tiring.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TEDDY
{DIALOGUE}: We're going to be here all night if we count every bill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT: A money-counting machine flips through the bills, its counter flying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The brothers rubberband it all in $100,000 decks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jot down the numbers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Put the money in newly-assembled file boxes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tape them shut.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 131 INT. CHEMICAL BANK - SAFETY-DEPOSIT ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Alone in the room, Frank transfers stacks of $100's from the file boxes into several open safety-deposit boxes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 132 INT. FRANK'S PENTHOUSE APARTMENT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The penthouse is now richly decorated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The R & B music playing through a state-of-the-art stereo system.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a kind of office party for Frank's brothers, cousins, wives and girlfriends, distributors like Rossi and other East Harlem guys, Charlie Williams, couple of cops on Frank's payroll, and the Chemical Bank Vice President.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANKER
{DIALOGUE}: You got a stockbroker, Frank?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I deal with enough crooks as it is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The banker jots down a name and phone number on the back of one of his business cards.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANKER
{DIALOGUE}: This one couldn't be more honest.
{DIALOGUE}: Ask around.
{DIALOGUE}: He's got a lot of clients in the business.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't leave all your money in safety deposit boxes; give him a call.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The banker hands him the card and moves on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank's trying to have a good time, but the level of noise and revelry is beginning to make him uncomfortable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHARLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: This is Mike Sibota.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sibota tries not to look as nervous as he feels.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 53.
{META_DATA}: 132 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Sibota.
{DIALOGUE}: What can I get you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SIBOTA
{DIALOGUE}: A left-hander from what Charlie tells me.
{DIALOGUE}: Your nephew?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank points to his nephew, Stevie, across the room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: It's been his dream all his life to play for the Yankees - and he's good enough.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SIBOTA
{DIALOGUE}: So I hear.
{DIALOGUE}: You have him come see me.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll give him a try-out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the scout hands his card to Frank, we whip over to where Teddy, his driver Jimmy Racine and their girlfriends, coked up, are laughing as a black cop, flashing his detective's shield, pretends to frisk Jimmy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: What's this?
{META_DATA}: (taking a .45 from Jimmy's pocket)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, that's it, I'm taking you in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JIMMY
{META_DATA}: (joking)
{DIALOGUE}: You can't take me in for that, I got a license for that, motherfucker.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{META_DATA}: (gives the gun back)
{DIALOGUE}: This then -
{META_DATA}: (the pile of coke on the coffee table)
{DIALOGUE}: But first -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cop sucks up a line before pretending to cuff Jimmy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: All right, now I'm arresting you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everybody laughs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teddy peels $100's from a money clip.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TEDDY
{DIALOGUE}: Let him go.
{DIALOGUE}: This is for you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: What is that, a bribe?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, now you're all under arrest.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 54.
{META_DATA}: 132 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cop pretends to arrest them all, but what he doesn't pretend is the hand he puts on Jimmy's girlfriend's breast as he frisks her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JIMMY
{DIALOGUE}: What is that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It was quick but Jimmy saw it, even though his girlfriend didn't react.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cop, oblivious, is cuffing Teddy now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm taking you all in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JIMMY
{DIALOGUE}: I said, what the fuck was that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DETECTIVE
{DIALOGUE}: What was what?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room explodes with a boom and the detective crumples to the floor, clutching at his leg, blood running through his fingers onto the carpet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank stares.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JIMMY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, he's all right.
{DIALOGUE}: I just shot him in the leg.
{DIALOGUE}: You got a health plan, what are you complaining about.
{DIALOGUE}: He's fine.
{DIALOGUE}: Here -
{META_DATA}: (peels off some money)
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred all right?
{DIALOGUE}: Six?
{DIALOGUE}: Look, he's feeling better all the time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, Frank grabs Jimmy and throws him against the wall.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 133 INT. FRANK'S PENTHOUSE APARTMENT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ana tries to clean the blood stain on the rug with salt and soda water, Frank sits with his five brothers in the debris-strewn aftermath of the party.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence before:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I can't have this kind of stupidity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TEDDY
{DIALOGUE}: It was an accident.
{DIALOGUE}: He feels terrible about it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: He doesn't feel shit, coked up all the time.
{DIALOGUE}: Get rid of him.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 55.
{META_DATA}: 133 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TEDDY
{DIALOGUE}: Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: He's your cousin.
{DIALOGUE}: What's he gonna do?
{DIALOGUE}: Go back home?
{DIALOGUE}: I'll talk to him.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll straighten him out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank looks at Teddy in his tinted Jackie Fox-like goggle glasses - like he's going to straighten anybody out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Gimme those glasses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TEDDY
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank pulls them from Teddy's face and crushes them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 134 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie sifts through the morning mail at his desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stops on an envelope from the New Jersey Bar Association.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he works up the nerve to open it, Spearman, Jones and Abruzzo organize the Italian wise guys' photos on the T.O.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: Ice Pick Paul goes here -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ABRUZZO
{DIALOGUE}: No, he's under Benny Two-Socks -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: No, you're thinking of Benny the Bishop.
{DIALOGUE}: Benny Two-Socks is Tosca's deadbeat son- in-law.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SPEARMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Jonesy's right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie comes over, studies the Table of Organization a moment, then begins untacking the photos from the top down -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: What're you doing?
{DIALOGUE}: We just -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: For a cop the uppermost thing is the arrest.
{DIALOGUE}: For a prosecutor, the arrest is nothing without the evidence to convict.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't have any real evidence on anyone on this board, so they're coming down.
{DIALOGUE}: We're starting over from the street.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 56.
{META_DATA}: 134 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ABRUZZO
{DIALOGUE}: What are you, a prosecutor all of a sudden?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie tacks his exam results onto the T.O.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passed.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 135 EXT. STREET - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie and the Amigos observe a buy from a parked car, the blue cellophane changing hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ignoring the buyer as he walks away, they keep watching the seller.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 136 EXT. GAS STATION / CAR WASH - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The seller is observed coming out of a mechanics garage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie ignores him as he walks away, watching instead the garage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually, a mechanic wiping his hands on a rag steps out, and Richie raises a camera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The image of the mechanic - a supplier - freezes -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 137 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A slightly-blurred photo of the mechanic goes up on a new, almost bare Table of Organization.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 138 EXT. GAS STATION / CAR WASH - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Atop of a telephone pole, Abruzzo, dripping with lineman equipment, works to attach a `slave' to the lines -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 139 INT. STOREFRONT APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bare room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie, Jones and Spearman eating take-out food as tape recorder reels turn.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PHONE VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Those snow tires you give me last time come in yet?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to want some more of them, gimme one and a half more of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The detectives laugh.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 140 INT. PROSECUTOR'S OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback has Richie sign a voucher for $20,000 cash.
