{DIALOGUE}: Cubans?
{DIALOGUE}: What.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TONY
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: All I can tell you is whoever it is, they're upsetting the natural order of things.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Among the framed family photos around them, is a picture of Tony's uncle, Albert Tosca.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 157 EXT. LIVINGSTON, NEW JERSEY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Napoleonic statue of the same man on horseback in a fountain outside a castle-like mansion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Next to it "ride" three others on marble horses - a woman and two children.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Pull -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A clay pigeon sails out across the manicured garden.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A shotgun blast shatters it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man with the gun - Albert Tosca - hands another to Frank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Frank sets to shoot, Ana can seen behind them, with Tosca's wife in the opulent house, looking uncomfortable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: The whole place was imported brick by brick from Gloucestershire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANA
{DIALOGUE}: It's very nice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Tosca nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ana nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A strained silence thicker than the tapestries settles over them until -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Pull -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The shotgun booms -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 158 INT. TOSCA'S MANSION - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As servants stand by, Tosca and his wife and their only guests - Frank and Ana - finished with lunch, get up from the table in the formal Formal dining room.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 64.
{META_DATA}: 158 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Mrs. Tosca leads Ana off to give her a tour of the house, the men head off the other way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: She's a lovely girl.
{DIALOGUE}: You should marry her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Too many things to look after right now to think about that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: That's a mistake.
{DIALOGUE}: If I may say.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't take her for granted, girl like that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They enter a rich, wood-paneled study lined with books.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: You interested in history, Frank?
{DIALOGUE}: The events that have brought us to where we are today?
{DIALOGUE}: You know who was?
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy was interested in a lot of things.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: I always wonder if people know when history's being made.
{DIALOGUE}: And what they're doing at the time.
{DIALOGUE}: This, for instance, could be a historic moment, and you're sipping a glass of ice water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Droplets snake down Frank's glass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He senses Tosca has finally gotten around to why he was invited here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Bumpy and I did a lot of business together, as you know.
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever he needed, he'd come to me and I'd do my best to provide it.
{DIALOGUE}: He came to me, I didn't go to him, is the point I'm trying to make.
{DIALOGUE}: You know why?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't have what you needed.
{DIALOGUE}: You had what he needed.
{DIALOGUE}: We've always had to come to you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Until now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tosca studies Frank, who is a study in inscrutability.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 65.
{META_DATA}: 158 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Monopolies are illegal in this country, Frank, because no one can compete with a monopoly.
{DIALOGUE}: If they let the dairy farmers do that, half of them would go out of business tomorrow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just trying to make a living.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Which is your right.
{DIALOGUE}: Because this is America.
{DIALOGUE}: But not at the unreasonable expense of others.
{DIALOGUE}: That's un-American.
{META_DATA}: (he studies Frank)
{DIALOGUE}: You know the price you pay for a gallon of milk doesn't represent its true cost of production.
{DIALOGUE}: It's controlled.
{DIALOGUE}: Set.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I set a price I think is fair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: It's very unfair, in fact.
{DIALOGUE}: Your customers are happy, but what about your fellow dairy farmers?
{DIALOGUE}: You're not thinking of them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{META_DATA}: (very calmly)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm thinking of them as much as they ever thought of me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: I can see you're getting excited.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't get excited.
{DIALOGUE}: That's not why I invited you to my home.
{DIALOGUE}: To get excited.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank doesn't look excited at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's the picture of calm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tosca smiles benignly and gets up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Here, I got something for you.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 159 INT. TOSCA'S SMOKING ROOM - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tosca opens a humidor, takes out a couple of Cuban cigars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Now what if - I'm just thinking out loud - you sold some of your inventory wholesale and I helped with the distribution.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 66.
{META_DATA}: 159 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I don't need it.
{DIALOGUE}: I already got everything from 110th Street to Yankee Stadium, river to river.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Which is a little mom and pop store compared to what I'm talking about.
{DIALOGUE}: I could make you bigger than K-Mart.
{DIALOGUE}: L.A., Chicago, Detroit, Vegas.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm speaking nationwide.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'd guarantee you peace of mind.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I mean by that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank does.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a backhanded threat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tosca clips the cigars with a gold guillotine
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Frank.
{DIALOGUE}: You can see I'm a Renaissance man.
{DIALOGUE}: Unfortunately not all my people are as enlightened.
{DIALOGUE}: Ask them, What is civil rights, they don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: They're not as open to change from the way things are done and who's doing it.
{DIALOGUE}: But I can talk to them so there won't be any misunderstanding.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I mean by peace of mind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank knows, in truth, he's not being given any choice in this matter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, maybe it's not so bad.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You pay what a kilo now, 75, 80?
{DIALOGUE}: I'd consider 50.
{DIALOGUE}: And I can get you as much as you want.
{DIALOGUE}: Tosca slips on his best poker face.
{DIALOGUE}: Fifty thousand a kilo would be an extraordinary coup for him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: You see, I was right.
{DIALOGUE}: This is a historic moment.
{DIALOGUE}: You're going to be bigger than Bumpy himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands Frank one of the cigars, expertly prepared.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOSCA
{DIALOGUE}: Can't smoke it here, unfortunately.
{DIALOGUE}: Grace doesn't like it.
{DIALOGUE}: Take it with you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 67.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 160 INT/EXT. TOSCA'S MANSION - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Doc waits by the car as Frank and Ana walk toward him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Toscas wave goodbye from the front step of the mansion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank slips the cigar into his top pocket as they climb in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANA
{DIALOGUE}: Why would you trust these people, the way they look at you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: They look at me like it's Christmas and I'm Santa Claus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANA
{DIALOGUE}: They looked at us like we're the help.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{META_DATA}: (kisses her cheek)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: They're working for me now.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 161 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A TV: Muhammad Ali, the black man's black man, and Joe Frazier, the white man's black man, at their 1971 Madison Square Garden press conference where Ali says as much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Most of the guys watching it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie isn't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes over to Table of Organization.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tacks his Bar Association notice to it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Regards the photographs, like tentacles of octopus yet to have a head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only the lowest section is made up of blacks (including Charlie Williams and Jackie Fox, but not Frank Lucas).
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rest of the faces are white and stop about midway up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They've hit a wall they can't get past.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 162 INT. FRANK'S PENTHOUSE - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another TV here: Howard Cosell, ringside at the Garden as the first early fans arrive, pointing out that the fight, because of the political stand Ali's taken, is less about boxers than war versus anti-war.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank chooses a linen jacket from his extensive color- coordinated racks of Phil Cromfeld suits as Ana, in her lingerie, puts on make-up at a vanity.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes up behind her and sets down a small jewelry box.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 163 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - SAME TIME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The TV in the background as Richie puts a camera with a long lens in a sports bag and reaches for his coat -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 68.
{META_DATA}: 163 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 164 OMIT 164 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 165 INT. FRANK'S PENTHOUSE - CONTINUED
