{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: C303 INT. FRANK'S PENTHOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes down the stairs to where Doc waits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they head for the door -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. LUCAS
{DIALOGUE}: Frankie -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank glances to where his mother sits in the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nods to Doc to say, Get the car, I'll be out in a minute.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Goes over to his mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. LUCAS
{DIALOGUE}: Sit down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She studies him in a way she hasn't since he was little.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. LUCAS
{DIALOGUE}: If you'd have been a preacher, your brothers would be preachers.
{DIALOGUE}: If you'd been a soldier, they'd be soldiers.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know that?
{META_DATA}: (he doesn't say)
{DIALOGUE}: They all came here because of you.
{DIALOGUE}: You called and they came running.
{DIALOGUE}: They look up to you.
{DIALOGUE}: They expect you to always know what's best.
{META_DATA}: (pause)
{DIALOGUE}: But even they know you don't shoot cops.
{DIALOGUE}: Even I know that.
{DIALOGUE}: Ana knows it.
{DIALOGUE}: You seem to be the only one who doesn't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Is that where I'm going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. LUCAS
{DIALOGUE}: I never asked you where all this came from because I didn't want to hear you lie to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't lie to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't do that, too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's not pleading, she's telling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 112.
{META_DATA}: C303 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. LUCAS
{DIALOGUE}: Do you really want to make things so bad for your family they'll leave you?
{DIALOGUE}: Because they will.
{DIALOGUE}: She will -
{META_DATA}: (points upstairs)
{DIALOGUE}: I know I will.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank has some trouble looking at her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But then gets up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walks toward the front door to leave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hesitates near it a long moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then turns and walks upstairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo will live, at least for now, because of her.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: D303 INT. ARMY HOSPITAL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Down in the basement, the body bags are lifted from the wooden coffins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Set down on tables.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bags unzipped and the bodies removed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A rack of clean uniforms is brought in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The morticians begin dressing the corpses and applying make-up on the dry gray skin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: New white military caskets are trundled in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gold handles lifted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bodies, clothed and painted now, are deposited on the silk linings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lids of the coffins come down and cellophane bags containing folded flags are taped on top.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 303 - 309 OMIT 303 - 309 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 310 EXT. ARMY HOSPITAL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The white caskets are taken to a loading dock, put in a military truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Papers are signed, copies exchanged.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the truck drives off -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 311 INT. ARMY HOSPITAL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two black privates on janitorial duty come into the room where the original plain wooden coffins have been discarded.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They remove the lids, then the finely-crafted false bottoms, revealing in 4-inch cavities of each, tightly-packed bricks of Double UO Globe heroin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they take them out, a gospel choir begins and continues over:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 312 EXT. ARMY HOSPITAL - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A laundry truck idles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stevie, the Lucas nephew who could have played for Yankees, jumps down, helps the two privates toss several laundry bags into the back of the truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 113.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A313 EXT. BAPTIST CHURCH - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A minister on the steps welcomes the congregation which includes Frank, his mother, and Ana -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 313 EXT. PERIMETER OF THE ARMY BASE - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The laundry truck comes past a guard gate, leaves the base, drives past a stand of trees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As it passes, Richie, parked by his detectives' cars, recognizes the young driver - who's wearing the same Yankee baseball cap in his T.O. photo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Richie and his detectives climb into their cars, two Lucas cars fold in behind the laundry truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The detectives follow at a distance -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A314 OMIT A314 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 314 INT. BAPTIST CHURCH - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sea of ladies' hats from above move in time with the gospel choir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As always, no matter what else is going on in his complicated life, Frank sits with his mother and Ana in their usual pew.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The gospel music continues over:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A315 EXT. BAPTIST CHURCH - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank emerges from the church, kisses his mother and Ana and put them in a car with a driver.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs into Doc's alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His mother watches, wondering perhaps if he intends to go kill Trupo after all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Doc's car leaves, so does another.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 315 - 318 OMIT 315 - 318 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 319 INT/EXT. RICHIE'S CAR - MOVING - NEAR GW BRIDGE - MORNING19 3
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The laundry truck approaches a ramp leading to the George Washington Bridge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie, a couple of car lengths behind, follows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The truck continues straight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 320 OMIT 320 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 321 EXT. NEWARK - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From overhead, the laundry truck, the gun car and the van - and the detectives' cars following them all - converge from different directions -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 114.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 322 EXT. NEWARK - NEAR STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Red Top's van makes a turn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Abruzzo's makes the same turn behind it, the infamous Stephen Crane Projects rise up in his windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His foot comes off the gas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the gun car passes, he sees Jones's car slow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teddy's car approaches from another direction into the Projects, and Abruzzo sees Spearman pull over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then the laundry truck turns in, and Richie's slows to a stop, like Abruzzo's, outside the grounds of the foreboding towers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The gospel music ends.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A323 EXT. CEMETERY - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Doc waits in the car while Frank buys some flowers at a cemetery flower stand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The surveillance car cruises past.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 323 INT. TOBACK'S HOUSE - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback, in his bathrobe, glass of milk in one hand, phone in the other ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: Where is it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE V/O
{DIALOGUE}: Somewhere in the South tower.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK
{DIALOGUE}: You know that it's there.
{DIALOGUE}: You're sure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE V/O
{DIALOGUE}: Positive.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 324 EXT. STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - SAME TIME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie, on a pay phone across down the street from the Projects, looks up at the dark South tower.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Lou.
{DIALOGUE}: We're ready to go in there knowing there's a good chance we won't all come out.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what we're willing to do.
{DIALOGUE}: All I'm asking you to do get me a warrant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence on the other end of the line ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: We don't have a lot of time to fuck around -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 115.
{META_DATA}: 324 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBACK V/O
{DIALOGUE}: I'll call in the warrant.
{DIALOGUE}: And some backup.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't go in before either gets there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This call disconnects.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 325 INT. APARTMENT, THE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls spread and tape plastic sheeting to tabletops, then begin changing for work, which means undressing.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 326 EXT. STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie and his guys wait for the warrant by their cars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JONES
{DIALOGUE}: How long we gonna wait for it?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 327 INT. APARTMENT, THE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pharmaceutical scales balance to their counterweights as the five naked, masked women cut the heroin with quinine to Frank's exacting standards.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Red Top puts on some coffee.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 328 EXT. STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie stares down the street, waiting for whatever it is they're waiting for.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spearman looks at his watch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: It'll be here.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 329 INT. APARTMENT, THE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A paper-cutter blade slices a sheet of blue cellophane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls at the tables, with the expertise of Cuban cigar makers, wrap pieces of the cellophane like tobacco leaves around precisely-measured 1/4-ounce drifts of Black Magic.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A330 EXT. CEMETERY - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank's car winds up the road of the cemetery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The surveillance car comes through the main gate and parks.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 330 EXT. STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several black and white and undercover cars approach, sirens off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Toback himself climbs out of one of the cars and hands Richie the search warrant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 116.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 331 EXT. STEPHEN CRANE PROJECTS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tall buildings cast long shadows of dread on every activity below, no matter how routine: A woman pushing a stroller, guys shooting hoops, a couple arguing, kids on bikes, old men resting on a graffiti-covered bench.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The unmarked cars drive slowly through it all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place teeters on the brink of violence you can feel as gangs move under the shadow of the towers.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 332 INT. GROUND FLOOR, SOUTH TOWER, THE PROJECTS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie removes the cover plate of an elevator, cuts the wires, disengaging it, then leads the Amigos, followed by more detectives to a stairwell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place is like Beirut.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Debris-strewn, graffiti-covered.
{META_DATA}: A333 EXT. CEMETERY - CONTINUED - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank walks past graves to Bumpy's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Replaces some dried flowers with fresh ones.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looks around for something to sit on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sees some wooden folding chairs around a fresher grave nearby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Doc waits by the car in the distance.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 333 INT. STAIRWELL - FLOORS - SOUTH TOWER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Floor by floor, they work their way up the tower like commandos, the squalor and decay and hopelessness somehow intensifying the higher up they go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the 17th floor, they listen to a strange sound before easing the fire door open enough to see a kid on a Big Wheels pedalling straight at them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passes and the sound fades.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 334 INT. 17TH FLOOR HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Half the apartment doors are gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TVs and radios echo, voices argue, infants wail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The detectives come around a corner and see at the end of it: a couple of guys with a sawed-off shotguns sitting outside a closed door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They step back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Consider one other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spearman volunteers with a nod, continues on alone as the others wait.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks up to the guys with the guns.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SPEARMAN
{DIALOGUE}: I got to talk to Teddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUY WITH GUN
{DIALOGUE}: Get the fuck out of here.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 117.
{META_DATA}: 334 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SPEARMAN
{DIALOGUE}: What the fuck is that?
{DIALOGUE}: I got business with Teddy and it's none of your fuckin business except to knock on the fuckin door and get him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the guy stands, pumping the shotgun, Spearman yanks it hard against his throat like a garrote, forcing him to the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The shotgun explodes, showering plaster and pellets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jones and Abruzzo are instantly all over the other guy as Richie swings the sledgehammer into the door -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 335 INT. APARTMENT, THE PROJECTS - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door splinters - the room already in chaos - Teddy, panicked, runs for the bedroom - the detectives crash in yelling at the girls to get down - a shot from somewhere inside wings Abruzzo - Jones and Spearman firing back - crawling across the floor like an infantrymen -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie comes into the darkened bedroom leading with his pistol.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Teddy's gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees a tapestry of a tiger on a wall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pulls at it, finds a big hole knocked into another dark apartment, climbs through, sees an open door -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 336 INT. THE PROJECTS BUILDING - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Richie rushes out to the hallway he can hear footfalls echoing in the stairwell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts down, taking the stairs five at a time, chases Teddy down two flights -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teddy yanks open a door, runs down a corridor, bangs into an apartment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie reaches the apartment just as Teddy is goes out onto an exterior balcony - Richie continues along the interior corridor, running parallel to Teddy on the balcony, who trips over some debris and garbage, looking over his shoulder for Richie -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie cuts through another apartment to head him off, but the door to the balcony is nailed shut.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: So are the windows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie looks around, grabs a small portable television and, just as Teddy runs past, hurls it through a window at him, hitting him in the head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He falls hard, dazed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie hurries through the broken window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teddy comes to and fights back, until Richie breaks his femur with his bare hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teddy howls in excruciating pain -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 337 INT/EXT. DRY CLEANERS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Police cars outside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eugene Lucas is cuffed and led away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 118.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 338 EXT. METAL DOOR SHOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More police outside Lester's place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They cuff him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 339 EXT. TIRE SERVICE SHOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: New Jersey troopers cuff Turner Lucas and lead him away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 340 EXT. ELECTRICAL SHOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cuffed, Earl Lucas is put in the back of a patrol car.
{META_DATA}: 341 EXT. CEMETERY - CONTINUED - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank, on a wooden folding chair at Bumpy's grave, hears the gunning of engines and barking of cops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to see Doc being handcuffed on the ground by the Towncar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Glances to a lone figure walking toward him over a rise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie arrives at the grave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Regards the monument to Ellsworth Johnson, and Frank sitting calmly regarding him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie glances around the peaceful surroundings ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: What kind of trees are these?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank looks at the trees, then at Richie, with equal serenity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You think you got Frank Lucas.
{DIALOGUE}: You got nothing.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A342 INT. RICHIE'S APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie cuts the tags off a new, inexpensive suit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slips the jacket on, which seemed somehow to fit a little better at the store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cuts the tags off a tie.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: B342 INT. COURTHOUSE MENS ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Someone throwing up in a stall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The toilet flushes, the door opens and Richie steps up to a sink, regards his face in the mirror.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under the fluorescent lights - maybe under any kind - his skin is a shade of death.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He splashes water on it and tries to gather himself.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 342 INT. COURTROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the prosecutors table, Richie steals glances at the battery of expensive attorneys over at the defense table.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 119.
{META_DATA}: 342 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The courtroom doors swing open and Richie sees Frank Lucas, in a tailored suit, escorted in without cuffs by an amiable- looking federal marshal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Frank moves through the gallery, Richie sees it's full of the gangster's friends, many of them celebrities, who smile and greet and fawn as if the Pope has arrived.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie has evidence tables covered with cash, weapons, stocks, bonds, property deeds, pictures of Frank's holdings, heroin in blue cellophane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank has celebrities, community leaders, Joe Louis himself who will testify to Frank's benevolent character.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Champ hugs the heroin trafficker warmly in front of everyone and Richie wonders if he should just give up now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie sees it in slow motion: the hands reaching out to Frank, the pats on his back, lipsticked mouths of beautiful women offering kisses and words of encouragement, his old mother giving him a hug.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He watches Frank's head turn slowly, his eyes passing his phalanx of attorneys, the jury, finally settling on Richie in his cheap suit seated at the prosecutors table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank's eyes smile as they regard Richie, and seem to ask, Can you see this - can you see what you're up against - can you see how insignificant you are?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the end of the welcoming line finally, Frank brushes by Richie and disappears from view somewhere within the protective husk of his multi-million-dollar legal team.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Roberts -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie slowly lifts himself from his chair, steps forward, turns to look at the jury that's studying him, finally finds his voice:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, your Honor.
{DIALOGUE}: Ladies and gentlemen -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 343 INT. COUNTY JAIL - INTERVIEW ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wire mesh separates Frank from his battalion of lawyers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He glances over them to Richie being led through the large Visiting Room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Here he is, let me talk to him alone.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 120.
{META_DATA}: 343 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The attorneys get up and leave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie takes their place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank regards him a moment, offering the same knowing smile from the courtroom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie offers nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I just heard something.
{DIALOGUE}: I said it couldn't be true.
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't really turn in a million dollars you found in the trunk of a car, did you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie doesn't say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank searches his face for some clue to where on earth he's from.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Want me to tell you what happened to it?
{DIALOGUE}: It ended up in cops' pockets.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe?
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: It did.
{DIALOGUE}: All you did was give it to them for nothing in return.
{DIALOGUE}: Not nothing: You got their contempt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank studies him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Why'd you do that?
{DIALOGUE}: What're you trying to prove, you're better than them?
{DIALOGUE}: You're not better than them.
{DIALOGUE}: You are them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't have the time or interest to listen to (this) -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You did it because it was right.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all.
{DIALOGUE}: Why's that hard to say?
{DIALOGUE}: The question is would you do it again?
{DIALOGUE}: That was a long time ago.
{DIALOGUE}: It'd be very easy to find out.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me you want to find out, tell me the address, and a car will be there, the trunk loaded.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie knows Frank isn't kidding ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: No, thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank suddenly explodes -
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 121.
{META_DATA}: 343 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Who the fuck are you to say no to that?
{DIALOGUE}: You think that impresses me?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Guards look over, then glance away once it's clear the outburst is through.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie remains serene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Let me ask you something.
{DIALOGUE}: You think by putting me in jail, you're going to stop even one junkie from dying?
{DIALOGUE}: Because you won't.
{DIALOGUE}: If it isn't me, it'll be someone else.
{DIALOGUE}: With me or without me, nothing's going to change.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Then that's the way it is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You have any sort of case?
{DIALOGUE}: Or just that idiot drives for my brother.
{DIALOGUE}: Is he your case?
{DIALOGUE}: Because if it's just him and the powder, it's not enough.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Then you got nothing to worry about.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Frank is worried, most of all by this cop who doesn't take money sitting placidly in front of him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: My brothers won't talk to you.
{DIALOGUE}: My cousins.
{DIALOGUE}: None of my family.
{DIALOGUE}: No one but that mother fucking driver.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I got more than that.
{DIALOGUE}: I got a line of people wanting to testify that stretches out the door and around the block.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Bullshit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Is it?
{DIALOGUE}: Tony the Bug.
{DIALOGUE}: Benny Two-Socks.
{DIALOGUE}: Carmine Camanetti.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Who the fuck are they?
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know them and they don't know me.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 122.
{META_DATA}: 343 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: They sell dope for the Mazzano crime family.
{DIALOGUE}: Which you all but put out of business.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: This is who you're going to put on the stand?
{DIALOGUE}: Guys who don't know me?
{DIALOGUE}: Who got nothing to do with me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: They have everything to do with you.
{DIALOGUE}: And the only thing they hate more than you is what you represent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I don't represent nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You don't?
{DIALOGUE}: Black businessman like you?
{DIALOGUE}: Of course you do.
{DIALOGUE}: But once you're gone, things can return to normal.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Look at me.
{DIALOGUE}: You looking?
{DIALOGUE}: Can you tell by looking it would mean nothing to me if tomorrow you turned up dead?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Get in line.
{DIALOGUE}: That one stretches around the block, too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank has never been so frustrated by anyone in his life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wants to work something out with Richie obviously, but he can't figure out how.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank studies him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: What can we do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You know what you have to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank does, but doesn't like it, and doesn't know if he can do it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I could give you cops, but that's not who you want, is it.
{DIALOGUE}: You want organized crime names.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take them, too.
{DIALOGUE}: I want them all.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 123.
{META_DATA}: 343 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank isn't sure he heard right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You'll take them, too?
{DIALOGUE}: You'd go after cops?
{DIALOGUE}: Are you serious?
{DIALOGUE}: You'd do that?
{DIALOGUE}: Lock up your own kind?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: They're not.
{DIALOGUE}: Not the ones in business with you.
{DIALOGUE}: They're not my kind any more than the Italians are yours.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They regard one another in silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie can tell Frank sees daylight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: What can you promise me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I can promise you if you lie to me about one name, you'll never get out of prison.
{DIALOGUE}: Lie about one dollar in one offshore account, you'll never get out.
{DIALOGUE}: You can live rich in jail the rest of your life, or poor outside it, that's what I can promise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank is silent for several moments.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You know, I don't care if the feds take all my buildings, my stocks, my off-shore accounts.
{DIALOGUE}: They can take it all, I don't care - use it to build battleships, paint bridges, whatever the fuck they want.
{DIALOGUE}: Fight another war.
{DIALOGUE}: But those other motherfuckers - the cops - put my money in their pockets.
{DIALOGUE}: Millions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I believe it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank debates with himself the step he's about to take ...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I want to know everyone you've met for the last twenty years.
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone you sold to.
{DIALOGUE}: Every cop you ever paid off.
{DIALOGUE}: Every one who ever stole from you.
{DIALOGUE}: Every one you remember.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 124.
{META_DATA}: 343 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I remember them all.
{DIALOGUE}: That's not the problem.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: What is?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: The jail's aren't big enough.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 344 INT. COUNTY JAIL CELL / STREETS OF NEW YORK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Surveillance photographs of cops seen earlier taking envelopes of money on 116th Street and other drops go up on a new, elaborate Table of Organization - of cops.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 345 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie dismantles the Lucas Table of Organization here, taking down the photographs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As it collapses -
{META_DATA}: 346 INT. COUNTY JAIL CELL - CONTINUED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank puts up photographs of detectives -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 347 QUICK CUTS of the same detectives, in handcuffs, led through 347 police stations past other cops watching with dread like maybe they're next -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A surveillance photograph of the four Princes of the City striding down a sidewalk goes up on the cell wall -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 348 FLASHCUT as three of the four SIU cops are led away in cuffs 348 from a golf course - 349 A surveillance photograph of Trupo in a black hand -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You go up here.
{DIALOGUE}: Your "special."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Frank tapes the picture of Trupo at the top of the pyramid of corruption -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 350 INT/EXT. TRUPO'S GARAGE - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trupo, coffee in hand, comes into his garage from his kitchen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Opens the garage door and sees two squad cars parked outside ...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 351 A TV: A report on the indictments handed down by the Manhattan DA's office against 53 NYPD and SIU detectives -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 125.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 352 INT. PRISON CELL - DAY (YEARS LATER)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank gathers his few personal belongings and puts them in a box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stands with the box and waits for the cell door to open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Table of Organization and files are gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: Frank Lucas was convicted of Conspiracy to Distribute Narcotics and sentenced to 70 years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He served 15 of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: Federal authorities confiscated over 250 million dollars from him in real estate, equities and cash in US and foreign banks.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 353 INT. NARCOTICS SQUAD HQ - NEWARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie, too, is packing, putting personal items into boxes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: The day after he convicted Frank Lucas and 30 of his Country Boy relatives, Richard Roberts borrowed $400 from his credit union to help pay for a 3-day vacation to the Bahamas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie, carrying the box, switches off the lights and closes the door behind him on his way out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Legend: Six months later, he quit the Prosecutors Office to become a defense attorney.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His first client was Frank Lucas.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 354 EXT. PRISON - DAY (1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank steps out into sunlight, free but owning nothing but the cardboard box in his arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looks out across the parking lot to see if anyone has come to pick him up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sees Richie by his car, hand raised above his head like a flag.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 355 EXT. 116TH STREET, HARLEM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two of them stand outside Richie's car on the same corner Frank shot Tango.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank looks up at the street signs that used to say 116th Street and 8th Avenue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now they say 116th Street and Frederick Douglass Boulevard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Frederick Douglass Boulevard?
{DIALOGUE}: What was wrong with just plain 8th Avenue?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He considers the street itself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It too has changed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The corner groceries, as Bumpy prophesied, really are gone now.
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 126.
{META_DATA}: 355 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I used to sit here with Ana in my old car.
{DIALOGUE}: She hated it.
{DIALOGUE}: Now I don't even have a car.
{DIALOGUE}: Or her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank glances to where his favorite diner used to be, and across the street to where he shot Tango.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It isn't a fruit stand any more.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Just do what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: The fuck is that?
{DIALOGUE}: Just do what?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a Nike store with huge paintings of Michael Jordan and the admonition "Just Do It."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Sneakers.
{DIALOGUE}: Expensive ones.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Who the fuck would buy those?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A car equipped with sub-woofer bass comes booming past.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank stares at it with the same pained look Bumpy had at the discount emporium.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Your brothers know you're out?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't talked to them in years.
{DIALOGUE}: It's better that way.
{DIALOGUE}: For them.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know where they are.
{DIALOGUE}: Went back to Greensboro when they got out, I guess.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Richie nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank looks back at the new storefronts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: What am I going to do now, be a janitor?
{DIALOGUE}: What do I know how to do?
{DIALOGUE}: How am I going to live?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: I told you I wouldn't let you starve.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: You told me but you can barely take care of yourself.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 127.
{META_DATA}: 355 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (glances to a pay phone on the corner)
{DIALOGUE}: You know, one phone call, Richie, I could be back in business.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The look Richie gives him calmly assures Frank if he did that it'd be the last phone he made outside prison - ever.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: I won't.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just saying I could.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He buttons the cuffs of the fake Members Only windbreaker Richie bought him off the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks for the clothes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RICHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You're welcome.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank glances away to three young hoods coming toward them like they own the sidewalk and everything around it - baggy pants, bandanas tied around their heads.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-oh.
{DIALOGUE}: Look out.
{DIALOGUE}: Here come the gangsters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank's right in their path but doesn't move, forcing one of them to squeeze between him and a parking meter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The gangsta looks back, is about to say something, or do something, but, examining the expression of quiet menace on Frank's face, thinks better of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The others stop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GANGSTA 2
{DIALOGUE}: What.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The first one is still staring at Frank, but finally has the good sense to let it go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GANGSTA 1
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They move on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank glances to Richie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Every idiot gets to be young once.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank zips up his Members Only jacket, props up the collar and points himself in the other direction.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRANK
{DIALOGUE}: Let's get out of here.
